  "texts": [
    "The GOLF FrameworkFigure 1 presents the GOLF framework, which includes a task taxonomy and outlines the process for task management under this framework.",
    "To elucidate the GOLF framework's structure and approach, Figure 1a depicts an analogy with the game of golf.",
    "In golf, players aim to sink the ball into a series of holes on the course with the fewest strokes possible, navigating recommended paths (blue dashed lines) and overcoming the challenge of landing spots (red pointers) between flags.",
    "Similarly, the GOLF framework envisions the completion of complex tasks as a strategic journey towards a final goal, incorporating a sequence of activities, tasks, and subtasks.",
    "This task taxonomy in Figure 1b decomposes complex human tasks from the information-seeking aspects [25], while the GOLF framework considers three types of subtasks: information-seeking, decision-making, and physical-action tasks, based on human information processing theory and task management principles."
  ],
